PropertyPath — Full Audit
What You've Built
PropertyPath is an educational web app guiding NSW property buyers through an 8-stage purchase journey. It's built on React 19 + TypeScript + Vite + Tailwind + shadcn/ui, with 23 interactive calculators, 24 persona-specific guides, a professional directory, and a warm-referral monetization model.

The Scores
1. Content — 8/10
What's strong:

150K+ words across 24 journey guides (8 stages × 3 personas), 10 reference articles, 7 question scripts, and 24 checklists. That's a serious content operation.
Persona-aware tone — FHB content is empathetic and cautionary, investor content is analytical and direct. This shows real thought.
Authoritative sourcing — citations from Revenue NSW, APRA, ATO, Housing Australia. Builds trust.
Calculator accuracy — the Stamp Duty calculator uses actual 2024-25 NSW brackets, includes FHBAS exemptions, foreign purchaser surcharge, and FHOG. Same for other tools.
General advice disclaimers are present and appropriately worded.
Reference library is genuinely useful standalone content.
What's holding it back:

Factual errors exist — the QA report flags outdated Home Guarantee Scheme caps, oversimplified FHOG thresholds, and even VIC/QLD stamp duty references snuck into NSW content.
Text-only delivery — no video, no audio, no embedded explainers. Property is visual; the content is not.
Downsizer persona is hollow — barely any referral CTAs, lighter content. It's an afterthought.
No "content freshness" signals — no "last updated" dates visible to users, no "this policy changed in 2025" callouts.
2. Flow — 6.5/10
What's strong:

Logical 8-stage architecture from Strategy → Settlement. Easy to understand.
Persona selection on entry gives users a tailored path.
Contextual referral CTAs appear at the right moments (e.g., building inspector CTA appears in Inspection stage).
Command search is a nice power-user feature.
Breadcrumbs on journey pages help orientation.
Lazy loading keeps initial load fast.
What's holding it back:

No progress persistence — close the tab and you're back at square one. No localStorage, no accounts, no "resume where you left off."
No guided sequence — users can jump to Stage 8 (Settlement) without reading Stage 1. An education app should scaffold learning, not just present a library.
Checklists don't save state — tick boxes reset on refresh. This kills utility.
No "next step" nudges — finishing a stage doesn't push you to the next one.
Calculator results aren't saveable or shareable — users lose their work immediately.
3. Design — 6/10
What's strong:

Clean and professional — shadcn/ui gives you a solid, consistent component language.
Custom design system — the HSC-inspired callout boxes, formula panels, worked examples, and key concept cards are distinctive and educationally effective.
Good responsive behavior — mobile nav, grid breakpoints, readable typography at all sizes.
Color logic — amber for warnings, teal for tips, navy for authority. Consistent.
What's holding it back:

Utterly forgettable visually — it looks like every other Tailwind + shadcn startup template. No brand personality, no photography, no illustrations, no emotional warmth.
Hero sections are walls of text — "Buy property with confidence" over a navy gradient is generic. Where are the people? The homes? The relief of getting keys?
Too corporate for the audience — first home buyers are anxious, excited, overwhelmed. The clinical navy-and-white aesthetic doesn't meet them emotionally.
No visual journey progress — a progress bar, a roadmap graphic, or a "you are here" indicator would massively help orientation.
Trust indicator misfire — "150K+ words of content" is not a user benefit. Users don't care how much you wrote.
4. Engagement — 5.5/10
What's strong:

23 calculators — this is your engagement engine. Borrowing power, stamp duty, rent vs buy, investment cashflow, life simulator. They work and they're useful.
Exit intent popup — smartly captures emails before users leave.
Free strategy call — low-friction entry point.
Interactive checklists and question scripts — practical tools users can take to meetings.
What's holding it back:

No gamification or progress mechanics — no badges for completing stages, no streaks, no "X% journey complete." Users need dopamine hits to keep going through 8 stages.
No community — property buying is social. No comments, no forums, no "see what others are asking."
No knowledge checks — no quizzes to reinforce learning. No "test your understanding" moments.
No sharing — can't share calculator results, can't send a checklist to a partner, can't bookmark a stage.
Passive reading experience — the journey content is markdown rendered as text. No accordion expandables, no "read more" reveals, no interactive scenarios.
No re-engagement mechanism — captured emails go nowhere. No drip campaign, no "here's what's next" emails.
